## System

 - **Operating System:** Windows 7
 - **Hardware:** Intel Wireless AC 7260 with Bluetooth 4.0
 - **Python Version:** 3.6.5
 - **PyBluez Version:** 0.23


## Issue
When attempting to connect to a device (LYWSD03MMC) using the code below, an OSError occurs:
```Python
import bluetooth;
from time import sleep;
print("creating socket");
socket_ = bluetooth.BluetoothSocket(bluetooth.RFCOMM);
print("connecting");
socket_.connect(("A4:C1:38:DF:xx:xx", 1));
print("waiting on connected...");
while not socket_.connected():
    pass;
print("connected successfully");
sleep(4);
print("now will disconnect");
socket_.close();
while socket_.connected():
    pass;
print("successfully disconnected");
```
Output:
```
creating socket
connecting
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "lywsblehelper.py", line 33, in <module>
    socket_.connect(("A4:C1:38:DF:xx:xx", 1));
  File "C:\Users\yardefaragunle\AppData\Local\Programs\Python\Python36\lib\site-packages\bluetooth\msbt.py", line 96, in connect
    bt.connect (self._sockfd, addr, port)
OSError: A
```

However, the device enquiry sample code (pybluez/examples/simple/inquiry.py) works as expected, showing both Classic BT and BLE devices:

Output:
```
performing inquiry...
found 9 devices
  30:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx - Lamp-007

  41:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx - iPhone
  54:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx - iPhone
  58:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx -
  84:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx - Nicholas Elliott (Galaxy S5)
  A4:C1:38:DF:xx:xx - LYWSD03MMC
  B8:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx -
  DF:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx - MX Master
  F8:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx -
```

Some observations that might help??
- My computer is able to connect to BLE devices, such as a mouse
- Another computer running Debian with a similar Intel adapter can connect to and communicate with the BLE device (LYWSD03MMC)

I was hoping to be able to develop a cross-platform client for this BLE device
